The Trojan Horse of Europe
BERKELEY – Europe will have no choice but to bail out Greece.
Emergency funds will need to be granted.
Conditions will need to be attached.
The Greek government will make the usual promises.
This should allow the Greek government to service its debt.
The markets will calm down.
The longer-term consequences will not be redemptive, but there will be problems to come.
Somewhere along the line, it will be said that the fatal error was allowing Greece to adopt the euro in the first place.
It was already clear that the country was not ready.
Its budgetary policy was already uncontrolled when it joined the monetary union in 2001, and its unions were already pressing for Greek wages to align with those practiced in Europe, despite lagging productivity.
But this response is too simplistic, as such signs of dysfunction do not confine themselves to Greece.
Spain, with an unemployment rate of 20% and abyssal budget deficits, sees Greece as an image of its own future.
And if that is not the case, the markets will take care of it.
Portugal and Italy fare slightly better.
Ces pays, tout comme la Grèce, doivent faire face à de fortes réductions de budget.
Comme la Grèce, ils ne peuvent pas procéder à une dévaluation de leur monnaie pour encourager les exportations.
Comme la Grèce, ils doivent faire face à une profonde récession.
Comme la Grèce, ils seront tentés de faire appel à l'aide.
Tout cela pose une seule question : la véritable erreur n'était-elle pas d'avoir créé l'euro ?
In the measure where I was one of the few Americans to encourage the idea of a European currency, you might ask whether I am reconsidering my initial position.
My answer is no, the fact of creating the euro has not been an error, but it could well become one.
The Greek crisis shows that Europe is only halfway on the path to a viable monetary union.
If it does nothing, the next crisis could well pass this one off as a stroll in the park.
If it wants to complete its monetary union, Europe will have to create its own emergency funding mechanism.
Aujourd'hui, the members of the Union can only help Greece by overstepping the regulation that prevents them from granting a loan except in the case of natural disasters or circumstances beyond the control of a country.
This exacerbates uncertainty.
When European leaders offer help, public opinion and the markets tend to question their honesty.
If the problems result from the Lisbon Treaty, then it must be amended.
In addition, aid should not be granted solely under certain conditions but should be accompanied by temporary budgetary control by a committee of "experts" appointed by the European Union.
L’histoire nous montre que de simples promesses émises par les pays bénéficiaires ne suffisent pas.
Bien sûr, les pays qui seront soumis à ce genre de mesures exprimeront leur indignation.
Mais, personne ne les oblige à accepter cet argent.
Des considérations morales ?
Voici votre solution.
Notice that this would be a much more effective disciplinary mechanism than the defunct Stability and Growth Pact.
We could also ask the following question: how would Californians react if their state temporarily put its budget in the hands of an expert appointed specifically by the administration of President Barack Obama?
Actually, they wouldn't mind that much.
The expert would not be from California, but from the United States.
The public would understand that he would act in the interest of the state of California as well as the country.
<s>California sends representatives to Washington, from which these orders would emanate, which would reassure them.
<s>Europeans do not do this kind of thing because they primarily see themselves as Greeks and Germans.
<s>They do not interfere with the "sovereignty prerogatives" of other member states.
<s>Germany is particularly hesitant given its history during World War II, especially in Greece.
<s>If Europe really wants to achieve its monetary union, it will have to overcome its past.
This union implies not only stronger economic ties but also closer political bonds.
Those who have a solid emergency aid mechanism will actually be held accountable.
They will have to answer to a strong European Parliament.
The electorate of German Chancellor Angela Merkel hates this kind of rescue because they know who will be footing the bill.
The Germans oppose anything that resembles European political integration.
But Germany has its share of responsibility in this crisis.
It wanted an incredibly independent central bank that was not required to account for its actions, but today it has adopted a monetary policy that is excessively tight, thereby exacerbating the critical situation of the PIIGS (Portugal, Ireland, Italy, Greece, and Spain).
The enormous current surpluses of Germany further worsen their situation.
Furthermore, its budgetary stimulus measures have not been sufficient to support the European economy.
Germany has benefited significantly from the creation of the euro.
She should do the same.
She should encourage the creation of an emergency lending facility, as well as the political integration necessary to make it possible.
She should provide more budgetary support.
Isn't she in the best position to push for a more responsible European Central Bank?
The Greek crisis could be the Trojan horse that leads Europe to a more thorough political integration.
On ne peut que l’espérer.
